 To find the perimeter of one of the five congruent rectangles, we need to consider the dimensions of the original rectangle and the division of the rectangle into five congruent rectangles.

The original rectangle has a length of 6 cm and a width of 5 cm. Since the rectangle is divided into five congruent rectangles, the length and width of each of the five rectangles will be half of the original rectangle's dimensions.

Length of each rectangle = (Original length) / 5 = 6 / 5 = 1.2 cm
Width of each rectangle = (Original width) / 5 = 5 / 5 = 1 cm

Now, we can find the perimeter of one of the five congruent rectangles by adding the length and width of each rectangle together.

Perimeter of one rectangle = (Length) + (Width) = 1.2 cm + 1 cm = 2.2 cm

So, the perimeter of one of the five congruent rectangles is 2.2 cm.

